    'investment' => 
    array (
      'title' => 'Numismatics as a form of investment',
      'lead' => 'The relationship between numismatic passion and market value.',
      'blocks' => 
      array (
        0 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'investimento_in_numismtica-2.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Staatliche Museen zu Berlin, The Money Changer by Rembrandt Harmensz. van Rijn (1606–1669)',
            'link' => 'http://www.smb-digital.de/eMuseumPlus?service=ExternalInterface&module=collection&objectId=868235&viewType=detailView',
          ),
          'body' => 'Since the coin first appeared in human history, it has always attracted the interest of all humanity, as it represents the Platonic idea of wealth, the most concise concept of value and preciousness, to the point of also being regarded as a diabolical instrument of evil. There is no disputing the attraction and attention that coins arouse, whether ancient or modern, metallic or paper. Probably thanks to these impulses, coins are the subject of one of the most complex forms of collecting. It should not be forgotten that these objects are often wonderful multiples of art, offering our eyes creations from civilisations far away in time and space. All the historical aspects that a series of them can retrace are exceptional, from portraits of emperors to depictions of monuments to commemorations of events.',
