            'alt' => 'numismatic investment, Brutus denarius, Ides of March denarius',
            'link' => '__ROUTE:guide.faq__',
          ),
          'body' => '<b style="text-align: left;">Ancient and modern coins</b> - As a general rule, ancient coins on the one hand and medieval, modern and contemporary coins on the other operate in markets with very different dynamics. The former are valued in an international context, while the latter are generally influenced by local markets. This means that the latter can be affected more than the former by conditions arising from internal dynamics in the country to which they refer. The choice of sector in which to direct purchases must also take this variable into account.<br><br><b>Condition and quality of coins and banknotes</b> - The world of collecting in general, and numismatics in particular, is increasingly focused on seeking perfect specimens or those of excellent quality; this also applies to numismatic objects. A sound investment therefore cannot ignore quality.',
        ),
        3 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'investire_in_numismtica.jpg',
            'alt' => 'numismatic investment',
          ),
          'body' => '<b style="text-align: left;">Evocative coins</b> - Coins that have never disappointed from an investment standpoint are those that in one way or another recall particular figures or events. A striking example is the denarius struck by Brutus after the assassination of Caesar.<br><br><b>The numismatic collection</b> - Assembling coins or banknotes while following the guidelines set out above is already a good starting point, but to achieve an excellent investment something “more” is needed: one must “collect”. To achieve good performance with coins, one must not overlook collecting and passion for these objects. No one is better placed than a careful collector to select their own coins. A collection also represents a broadly diversified portfolio of objects, which can offset any decline in value of some specimens with the rise of many others.',
        ),
        4 => 
