            'alt' => 'numismatic investment',
          ),
          'body' => '<b style="text-align: left;">Tax regulations</b> - The market for collectible coins and banknotes is subject to a special direct tax known as “margin VAT”. This VAT regime, in force throughout Europe, applies VAT (21% in Italy) only to the value added by the dealer on the price paid to the private seller. Overall, therefore, a minimal tax burden, which moreover does not apply to transfers between private individuals. This taxation also applies to commissions paid on auction sales. No tax is due in Europe on assembled numismatic holdings.<br><br><b>Example of appreciation</b> - A particularly fine and well-preserved sestertius of Hadrian was sold in the 1980s for 20 million lire; the same coin later achieved 300,000 dollars at an auction in New York in 1990. Recently, in 2009, the same sestertius reappeared on the market at an auction in Geneva, where it realised 2,000,000 Swiss francs! <br>Happy collecting — and good numismatic investing!<br>Umberto Moruzzi',
