    'rome_in_coins' => 
    array (
      'title' => 'The History of the Ancient Roman Coin',
      'lead' => 'Ancient Rome through numismatics.',
      'blocks' => 
      array (
        0 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'monete_romane_7g50r436.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Roman coin, Roman coins',
            'link' => '__ROUTE:guide.rome_in_coins__',
          ),
          'body' => '<b><a href="__ROUTE:guide.rome_in_coins__">Looking for a Roman coin? In Italy, the trade and collecting of ancient coins of lawful provenance is legal. Visit our Online Shop.</a></b><br>',
        ),
        1 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'l_marcius_philippus.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Roman coin, Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => '<b>Coins speak to us …</b><b class="fs14"><br></b>If we pay attention to the subjects represented on Roman coins, we can learn a great deal about life in ancient Rome. In Republican coinage, that multiplicity of subjects already apparent would remain unchanged throughout the imperial period. Between the themes of the two periods, however, there is a profound difference: in Republican times, the variety of types depends on the political manoeuvres of the moneyers, who choose subjects drawn from the history and legends of the gens to which they belong.',
        ),
        2 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'flamininus.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Roman coin, Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => 'During the Empire, by contrast, typological variety was controlled by the Emperor, and the achievements of figures other than the emperor himself or members of the imperial family no longer appear. Representations on Republican denarii of types referring to the moneyer or his family—the so-called family types—gradually began, from around the middle of the 2nd century BC. At this point the language of coins becomes rich in many meanings: for these magistrates, acquiring and maintaining power means referring to a glorious past, embodied at first in the figure of a mythical ancestor, then later commemorating the historical ancestor.',
        ),
        3 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'mamilius.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Roman coin, Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => 'Some magistrates, even though they did not possess an illustrious past to evoke and celebrate, created one, seeking a foothold in legendary tales and thus inventing mythical images. Such is C. Mamilius Limetanus, belonging to the gens Mamilia, who on denarii of 82 BC depicts on the reverse Argos the dog recognising Ulysses, and Mercury on the obverse. The magistrate recalls Mercury, protector of Ulysses, to whom he gave the magic herb to escape the enchantment of the sorceress Circe; from his union with the sorceress, Ulysses had a son, Telegonus, father of a maiden named Mamilia, founder of the gens, which thus boasts descent from a divinity.<br>',
        ),
        4 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'Q_Servilius_Cepio_L_Calpurnius_Piso.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Roman coin, Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => 'From coin representations it is possible to grasp many aspects of Roman life and history; coins tell us and "photograph" scenes of combat and voting, triumphs and sacrifices, monuments erected or restored, ancestral cults and new cults. All the deities worshipped at Rome appear on coins, even the minor or less well-known ones, and the personifications, the most frequent being Victoria, depicted in a biga or quadriga, standing or seated. From the end of the 2nd century BC, types celebrating the history and origins of the family of the moneyer who signs the coin become more numerous. For the first time, around 100 BC, a type relating to the very magistrates who sign the coin appears, commemorating contemporary events. This is a denarius attributed to the quaestors Q. Servilius Cepio and L. Calpurnius Piso, which bears on the reverse the two quaestors seated on a subsellium, among ears of grain and the legend AD FRV EMV EX S C (= ad frumentum emundum ex senatus consulto), recalling that the issue was struck by senatorial decree for the purchase of grain.',
        ),
        5 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'giulio_cesare.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Roman coin, Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => 'With the transition from Republican to imperial coinage, the propaganda character is accentuated, no longer focusing on the gens but on the figure who at that moment dominates the political scene. One of the greatest innovations in typology occurred with Caesar, most probably at the end of 45 BC, when, on the basis of a senatorial decree, Caesar had denarii struck with his own portrait. This was the first case where the image of a living person appeared, except for the sporadic case of the issue in the name of Titus Quinctius Flamininus, which, however, was struck in Greece and not at Rome. Certainly in the then-known world this privilege was well known. In the Hellenistic world, for already two and a half centuries, rulers had struck coins bearing their name and portrait. The honour granted to Caesar had no precedent at Rome and bore a regal significance. Caesar\'s example was followed by all the political men and generals who after him contested power; they did not overlook the significance of placing their own portrait on coins.',
        ),
        6 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'commodus_medallion.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Roman coin, Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => 'Even in the imperial period, with the representation of contemporary events, the coin continued, in its function of celebrating the figure of the emperor and his family, to be a guarantee of continuity in the governance of the empire. During the imperial period, the projection of the emperor\'s image and policy throughout the empire was accompanied by numerous means; among these was also the coin, as an official source which, thanks to its widespread diffusion, was well suited to be used as a vehicle of imperial propaganda. The imperial image occupying almost always the coin field served to make the emperor\'s features familiar in the various regions of the empire. The emperor, represented in profile, now to the right, now to the left, could be laureate, wear the radiate crown, dress in "civil" or military garb. Some coin reverses inform us that the fruits of the empire were peace, prosperity, wealth, all assured by the virtues of the princeps: the emperor was thus praised as defender of the empire.',
        ),
        7 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'vict_brit.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Roman coin, Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => 'Representations of Victoria were frequent, representing the concrete success of the legions, obtained under the supreme command of the princeps as imperator, and of Pax, the greatest benefit of victory. Imperial benefits were frequent themes in official sources, such as coins and monumental art; these themes included the organisation of spectacles, the construction of public works and buildings, and congiaria. The emperor was moreover associated on coins with the major deities: Pax, Salus Publica, Concordia, Libertas, Constantia, Pietas, Iustitia, Securitas and Victoria, personifications of public desires that become abstractions of imperial power. The emperor, like a Hellenistic king, was the saviour who defended the empire, the bearer of peace and joy.',
        ),
        8 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'cristogramma.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Roman coin, Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => 'The progressive spread of Christian motifs on coins after AD 313 deserves emphasis; however, they did not assume the function of main type, but remained at the level of symbols or as attributes of other figures: in this case too, the coin reflects not only political-economic but also cultural and religious aspects: of the ancient coin typology only the figure of the emperor and the types of Roma and Victory will remain, which will have a purely symbolic value.<br>Francesca Barenghi<br>',
        ),
      ),
    ),
    'aes_rude_signatum' => 
    array (
      'title' => 'The first Roman coins',
      'lead' => 'The earliest forms of money at Rome.',
      'blocks' => 
      array (
        0 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'monete_romane_7g50r436.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Roman coin, Roman coins',
            'link' => '__ROUTE:guide.rome_in_coins__',
          ),
          'body' => '<b><a href="__ROUTE:guide.rome_in_coins__">Looking for a Roman coin? In Italy, the trade and collecting of lawfully provenanced ancient coins is legal. Visit our Online Shop.</a></b><br>',
        ),
        1 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'aes_rudes.jpg',
            'alt' => 'aes rude, aes signatum, aes grave',
          ),
          'body' => '<b>WHEN ROME STILL DID NOT USE COINAGE......</b><b class="fs14"><br></b>Coinage was born at Rome in the last decades of the 4th century BC, after the conclusion of the First Samnite War (341 BC). Before the introduction of coinage, aes rude — that is, copper in shapeless pieces of variable weight, from over two kilograms to a few grams — was used as a medium of exchange at Rome and in Latium. The oldest hoards date back to the 7th century BC, the most recent to the 3rd century BC: by this time aes rude had lost its function as a means of payment and survived only as a votive offering. Ancient authors also mention this medium of exchange and measure of value; among them Pliny, who in a famous passage of the Naturalis Historia reports: "King Servius was the first to mark copper; Timaeus reports that rough copper was formerly used at Rome".',
        ),
        2 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'aes_rudes02.jpg',
            'alt' => 'aes rude, aes signatum, aes grave',
          ),
          'body' => 'Alongside aes rude, we later also find another medium of exchange: bronze cast in rectangular ingots with figural reliefs on one or both faces, therefore called aes signatum. The term aes signatum means copper with a signum, that is, with an imprint. It was used whole or in pieces, and three groups are known: the first comprises rougher and heavier pieces (up to 3.453 kg), characterised by linear figuration called "dry branch"; the second comprises less rough pieces whose figurations are the "fish bone", the star, the lunar crescent, the dolphin; the third group comprises pieces of which some are certainly of Roman origin, those bearing the inscription ROMANOM or ROM. When whole, their weight varies between 1.142 and 1.830 kg; they bear on both faces figures of animals such as the eagle, Pegasus, the pig, the bull, and other representations such as the sword, the caduceus, the shield, the tripod, the anchor, the trident. The exact function of these pieces, datable perhaps between the 4th and 2nd centuries BC, that is, at a time when true coinage was already in use, is not known.',
        ),
        3 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'aes_signatum02.jpg',
            'alt' => 'aes rude, aes signatum, aes grave',
          ),
          'body' => 'Unlike Greek usage, the practical Romans added to the emblems also certain marks indicating their value, using vertical strokes for units in pounds and globules for units in ounces. Because of their size the pieces were cast rather than struck. Aes signatum was already known by the mid-6th century BC, since a fragment with a dry branch was found at Bitalemi, near Gela, in the temple of Demeter and Kore, in a votive pit dated between 560 and 540 BC. The fragment must have reached Sicily probably through trade.',
        ),
        4 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'aes_signatum.jpg',
            'alt' => 'aes rude, aes signatum, aes grave',
          ),
          'body' => 'Where the workshops producing these ingots were located is still debated by scholars, but since so far the greatest number of finds has occurred between Bologna and Reggio, it is probable that the workshops producing these ingots were in the lower Po plain or in Etruria and that from these places they spread into Latium. It is certain that the use of rough copper and stamped copper lasted a long time, since numerous pieces have also been found together with coins. We must also remember another measure of value, namely "cattle-money", which is attested in the Latin language not only by certain terms derived from the word pecus (= cattle), such as pecunia (= money), peculium (= patrimony), peculatus (= embezzlement of public money), which we still find today, but also by what has been handed down by ancient authors. Festus informs us, for example, that the fine for minor offences was calculated at two sheep, for more serious ones it could reach up to thirty oxen. The Aternia-Tarpeia law dates to 454 BC, named after the consuls Aulus Aternius Varus and Spurius Tarpeius Montanus, and that of Menenia-Sestia to 452, from the consuls Titus Menenius Lanatus and Publius Sestius Capitolinus, which established that penalties could also be paid in copper and fixed the value of a sheep at ten asses and of an ox at one hundred asses.<br>Francesca Barenghi',
        ),
      ),
    ),
    'republican_rome' => 
    array (
      'title' => 'Republican Roman Coins',
      'lead' => 'The coinage of Republican Rome.',
      'blocks' => 
      array (
        0 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'monete_romane_7g50r436.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Roman coin, Roman coins',
            'link' => '__ROUTE:guide.rome_in_coins__',
          ),
          'body' => '<b><a href="__ROUTE:guide.rome_in_coins__">Looking for a Roman coin? In Italy, the trade and collecting of ancient coins of lawful provenance is legal. Visit our Online Shop.</a></b><br>',
        ),
        1 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'quadrigatoA.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Republican Roman coin, Republican Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => '<b>THE ROMANO-CAMPANIAN COINAGE</b>

<b class="fs14"><br></b>Only in the last decades of the 4th century BC did Rome begin to strike coin: it was at this time that the transition occurred from an economy in which transactions took place through metal, cast or struck, exchanged by weight, to monetary discs on which the state reserved the right to apply its "seals". In the Greek world this phenomenon had occurred much earlier, around the middle of the 7th century BC, with the first electrum coins struck in Asia Minor in the kingdom of Lydia and in the Greek colonies of Ionia.',
        ),
        2 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'quadrigatoB.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Republican Roman coin, Republican Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => 'On the Italian peninsula the cities of Magna Graecia had been striking coin for one or two centuries already; thus Rome, coming into contact with the populations of southern Italy at the time of the First Samnite War, could not avoid the necessity of having its own coin, though with characteristics that would make it suitable also for circulation outside Roman territory. This need was met with the issue of a series called by scholars "Romano-Campanian", since the coins bore the name of Rome but were struck in the mints of Campania, with a non-Roman weight system, and with types that were not those Rome had used until then, comprising issues in bronze, silver and gold.',
        ),
        3 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'sessanta_assiA.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Republican Roman coin, Republican Roman coins, martial gold',
          ),
          'body' => 'The first series bear the legend in Greek, constituting evidence of the destination of these issues for commercial exchange with the cities of Magna Graecia. This first approach of Rome with Campania was followed by another coinage with the Greek legend transcribed in Latin characters. Specimens belonging to the second series are very rare; it was probably a transitional series. Rome\'s need to strike silver coins, to be on a par with the cities of Magna Graecia, was met with a series of didrachms and drachms, with types deriving for the most part from those used by the cities of Magna Graecia and Sicily.',
        ),
        4 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'sessanta_assiB.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Republican Roman coin, Republican Roman coins, martial gold',
          ),
          'body' => 'The last issues, consisting of didrachms and drachms with Jupiter in a galloping quadriga on the reverse hurling the thunderbolt, are called by scholars "quadrigati".

<br>

In connection with this issue a series of gold issues was placed, called "oath gold", from the reverse type depicting two warriors, probably a Roman and a Samnite, swearing with spear and drawn sword over a piglet held by a kneeling man.

<br>',
        ),
        5 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'asse_romano_fusoA.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Republican Roman coin, Republican Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => '<b>THE AES GRAVE</b>

<br>In its urban mint Rome issued bronze coins, cast and not struck, weighing one libra for the as (272.87 gr.). <br>The as was divided into twelve unciae and had as sub-multiples the semis (equal to half an as), the triens (one third of an as), the quadrans (one quarter of an as), the sextans (one sixth of an as), and the uncia.',
        ),
        6 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'asse_romano_fusoB.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Republican Roman coin, Republican Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => 'All denominations bore the value mark impressed, but there was no legend, not even the name of Rome. The best-known series is the "prow" series, named after the ship\'s prow on the reverse of all denominations. On the obverse are depicted the major deities of the Roman pantheon: Janus on the as, Jupiter on the semis, Minerva on the triens, Hercules on the quadrans, Mercury on the sextans and Bellona on the uncia. This series continues throughout the Republican period, until the first half of the 1st century BC. Through a series of reforms the weight of the as was reduced from one libra to about half an uncia in 89 BC.

<br>',
        ),
        7 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'denario_anonimoA_ynmqrk2b.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Republican Roman coin, Republican Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => '<b>THE DENARIUS</b>

<br>According to the testimony of Pliny the Elder, "silver was coined in the 485th year from the foundation of the city, when Q. Ogulnius and C. Fabius were consuls, five years before the beginning of the First Punic War. And it was decided that the denarius should be worth ten librae of bronze, the quinarius five, the sestertius one dupondius and one semis". On the basis of the literal interpretation of Pliny\'s passage, scholars have dated the introduction of the denarius to 269 BC, and a few years later the striking of the "victoriatus", the silver coin weighing 3.41 grams, so called for the reverse type representing Victoria crowning a trophy.',
        ),
        8 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'denario_anonimoB.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Republican Roman coin, Republican Roman coins',
          ),
          'body' => 'In recent years other chronologies have been opposed to this one, starting from the assumption that Pliny\'s passage confuses Romano-Campanian coinage with the denarius, and based above all on the examination of coins and coin hoards.

<br>

According to a chronology proposed by H. Mattingly and E. Robinson, two English numismatists, the beginning of denarius coinage should be dated to 187 BC.<br>',
        ),
        9 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'aureo_giuramentoA.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Republican Roman coin, Republican Roman coins, oath aureus',
          ),
          'body' => 'This dating was refuted by finds from the excavations at Morgantina, where denarii, quinarii, sestertii and victoriati of the earliest issues were found in the temple of Demeter and Kore.

<br>

Since Morgantina was destroyed by the Romans in 211 BC, the introduction of the denarius must have been earlier, even if only slightly, than 211 BC.<br><b>GOLD COINS</b>',
        ),
        10 => 
        array (
          'type' => 'split',
          'image' => 
          array (
            'file' => 'aureo_giuramentoB.jpg',
            'alt' => 'Republican Roman coin, Republican Roman coins, oath aureus',
          ),
          'body' => 'In the Republican period Rome struck some rare gold issues. Among these is the "oath gold", of which we spoke previously, and gold with precise conversion into lower denominations. After these two first series, for more than a century there were no gold issues. Before Caesar\'s gold issues, three very rare series of gold coins are known: the first was struck by the consul Titus Quinctius Flamininus in 197 BC after the victory at Cynoscephalae over Philip V of Macedon; the second belongs to Sulla with types relating to the dictator\'s victories; the third is that of Gnaeus Pompey Magnus.<br>Francesca Barenghi',
        ),
      ),
    ),
